<subSubSection box="[198,1049,1965,1991]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1845,1991]" box="[198,1049,1965,1991]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1965,1991]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Very large orange elytral maculae are unique for this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,298]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,380,151,177]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Redescription.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[387,499,152,178]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Holotype</typeStatus>
, female. Body hemispherical, TL/EW 1.2, very convex, covered with yellowish suberect setae. Dorsum blackish brown with big, oval orange maculae in anterior half of elytra, reaching base of elytra, with oblique posterior margins, suture and outer elytral margin narrowly brownish-black; ventral side, epipleura, legs, mouthparts and antennae yellowish; antennae slightly darkened apically.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="23" pageNumber="24" startId="23.[151,255,1604,1628]" targetBox="[186,1405,388,1529]" targetPageId="23">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1604,1662]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,294,1604,1628]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">FIGURE 17.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Pic. A" authorityName="Pic. A" authorityYear="1916" box="[300,662,1604,1628]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="binotatus">
<emphasis box="[300,588,1604,1627]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Exochomoscirtes binotatus</emphasis>
Pic. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[642,662,1604,1628]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[662,670,1604,1628]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">)</emphasis>
female genitalia; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[861,888,1604,1628]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">B)</emphasis>
bursal sclerite; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1057,1085,1604,1628]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">C)</emphasis>
prehensor. Abbreviations: b. scl. – bursal sclerite; preh. – prehensor; gl – gland.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1754,2020]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Head covered with fine punctures, separated by ca. 1.0 diameter. Eyes big, moderately protuberant; head 1.7 X wider than interocular space. Antennae filiform, antennomere 1 subcylindrical, antennomere 2 subglobular, antennomere 3 elongate but narrow, antennomeres 4–11 slightly longer than antennomere 3. Palpomeres of maxillary palpi very wide.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1754,2020]" lastBlockId="24.[151,1437,152,658]" lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Pronotum slightly convex, covered with fine punctation, similar to that on head, separated by ca. 1.0 diameter, anterolateral corners projecting anteriorly; lateral margins straight; posterolateral corners almost acute; base of pronotum subtrapezoidal, with complete groove along basal margin; PW/PL 3.4. Scutellum punctured as on pronotum, equilaterally triangular. Angle between pronotum and elytra not marked in dorsal outline.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,152,658]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Elytra broadly oval, without traces of longitudinal ridges, with slightly explanate lateral margins, widest in the middle, punctation stronger than on pronotum, distance between punctures ca. 1.0–1.5 diameter; humeri well marked; EL/EW 1.1; EL/PL 6.1; EW/PW 1.6.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,152,658]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Legs moderately long. Hind tibial spurs well developed, the longer spur is slightly curved, almost as long as tarsomere 1, shorter spur curved, as long as 2/3 of the length of longer spur.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,152,658]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Ventrites 1 and 2 with sparse setation in mesal portions, ventrite 2 with basal row of numerous big punctures. Apex of ventrite 5 emarginated.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,152,658]" box="[198,1436,511,538]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,411,511,537]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Prehensor long (L 1.10), very narrow; bursal sclerite small, plate-like (L 0.20, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1333,1424,512,538]" degrees="0.14" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" precision="555" value="-0.14">W 0.14</geoCoordinate>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,152,658]" box="[198,383,552,578]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Male unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,152,658]" box="[198,1139,591,618]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,389,591,617]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Measurements.</emphasis>
Female (n = 1): TL 4.70, PL 0.70, PW 2.40, EL 4.25, EW 3.80.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,152,658]" box="[198,449,632,658]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Distribution. W 
<collectingRegion box="[389,445,632,658]" country="Indonesia" name="Jawa Timur" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Java</collectingRegion>
